# go vet allowance policy
#
# This project uses go vet strictly. Zero warnings are allowed at merge.
# The following conventions explain how we satisfy the unsafeptr and unkeyed checkers
# in the COM/WinRT interop code.

[conventions]

# 1. COM vtbl dispatch
# vtblMethod takes unsafe.Pointer and uses unsafe.Add to read function pointers
# from the vtable. This satisfies the unsafeptr checker because the interface
# pointer is typed as unsafe.Pointer (not uintptr), keeping the object rooted
# during the vtable traversal. See internal/actions/uia_com.go:86-89.

# 2. COM interface storage
# All COM interface pointers stored in struct fields are typed unsafe.Pointer
# instead of uintptr. This avoids the "possible misuse of unsafe.Pointer"
# warning when converting back to pass to syscall.SyscallN at call sites.

# 3. Syscall output parameters
# Local variables used as output parameters for SyscallN (written via
# uintptr(unsafe.Pointer(&var))) are declared as unsafe.Pointer when they
# receive pointer values. The syscall writes pointer-sized values regardless
# of the Go type, and this avoids a later unsafe.Pointer(uintptr_var) conversion.

# 4. GUID literals
# All windows.GUID literals use keyed fields (Data1, Data2, Data3, Data4)
# to satisfy the unkeyed composite literal checker.

# 5. RAW_SYSCALL_RESULTS
# When a syscall returns a uintptr that is a valid pointer (e.g.
# WindowsGetStringRawBuffer), we use reinterpretation through
# *(*unsafe.Pointer)(unsafe.Pointer(&uintptr_var)) to avoid the
# unsafe.Pointer(uintptr_var) pattern that vet flags.
# These are documented inline with a // SAFETY: comment at each site.
